Task: 2025-12-15__USER-PROFILES
Owner: Tech Lead Agent (proposal only; requires human approval)
Status: Draft for review

## 1) Goals & Scope (In-Task)
- Ship first-gen user-facing account surfaces:
  - Public profile pages (self + other).
  - Profile editing for MVP fields.
  - Account/settings page for non-payment, non-creator settings.
  - Avatar upload/update/remove.
  - Core layout + navigation (desktop side-nav, mobile top-nav).
- Reuse existing AUTH-SYSTEM (signed-in users) and design system (UI components/layout patterns).
- Keep clean separation of concerns per CODEBASE_ARCHITECTURE_RULES (dumb UI vs smart containers, services, repositories).

## 2) Requirements Decisions (from PM/Human)
- MVP profile fields (all from PM list):
  - Display name, username/handle, avatar, bio, location (optional), join date (read-only), follower/following counts (read-only).
- Public vs account-only:
  - Public profile: avatar, display name, handle, bio, (optional) location, join date, follower/following counts.
  - Account-only settings: email, legal name (if any), notification toggles, privacy toggles (profile discoverability, show/hide location).
- Navigation pattern:
  - Responsive hybrid: side nav on desktop + top nav on mobile.
- Avatar content:
  - NSFW avatars are allowed, subject to future moderation rules (copy should reference community guidelines; moderation infra is a separate task).

## 3) Domain Model (Conceptual – schema changes defined by engineering)
- User (extends AUTH-SYSTEM user):
  - id
  - email
  - username (unique handle, immutable or limited-change)
  - displayName
  - bio (short text)
  - location (optional)
  - avatarUrl (nullable)
  - isDiscoverable (profile discoverability toggle)
  - showLocation (bool)
  - joinDate (derived from createdAt)
- ProfileStats (can be denormalized or view):
  - userId
  - followersCount
  - followingCount
- NotificationSettings (coarse-grained MVP):
  - userId
  - basic toggles (e.g. emailNotificationsEnabled, marketingEmailsEnabled, platformUpdatesEnabled) – exact set can be finalized in engineering.

> NOTE: No enforcement of NSFW avatar policy here; that will live in separate moderation/flagging flows.

## 4) Layered Architecture (Backend)
- Route Handlers (Next.js App Router `app/api/**/route.ts`):
  - Thin HTTP mapping only; call exactly one controller each.
- Controllers (`src/app/api/_controllers/profileController.ts`, `settingsController.ts`, `avatarController.ts`):
  - Parse/validate request DTOs.
  - Call services.
  - Map domain results → HTTP responses.
- Services (`src/services/profileService.ts`, `settingsService.ts`, `avatarService.ts`):
  - Business logic for profile updates, visibility rules, ownership checks.
  - Enforce privacy decisions (what can be read/changed by whom).
- Repositories (`src/repositories/profileRepository.ts`, `settingsRepository.ts`, `statsRepository.ts`):
  - Pure DB/data access (Prisma).
  - No business rules, only queries and simple projections.
- Storage/Media client (`src/services/media/avatarStorageClient.ts` or reuse existing storage abstraction):
  - Wraps existing storage strategy (S3/Cloudflare/etc.) for avatars only.
  - Handles upload URLs, deletion, and path conventions.

## 5) HTTP/API & Routing Plan
High-level API surface (exact paths to align with `docs/05-API-SPECIFICATION.md` in engineering; here is the conceptual mapping):
- `GET /api/profile/me` – get current user's profile (including account-only fields, e.g. email, settings) for edit context.
- `GET /api/profile/[handle]` – public profile view by handle (public fields only).
- `PATCH /api/profile` – update profile fields (displayName, bio, location, discoverability, showLocation).
- `GET /api/settings` – fetch account + notification + privacy settings.
- `PATCH /api/settings` – update settings.
- `POST /api/profile/avatar/upload-url` – issue signed upload URL / upload token for avatar.
- `POST /api/profile/avatar/confirm` – confirm new avatar URL after successful upload.
- `DELETE /api/profile/avatar` – remove avatar, revert to default.

All routes:
- Must pass through shared auth middleware (session from AUTH-SYSTEM).
- Should use shared rate limiting middleware for write endpoints.

## 6) Core Flows
- View own profile:
  - Authenticated user → fetch `/api/profile/me` via container → render profile page using UI components.
- View other profile:
  - Route by handle → `/api/profile/[handle]` → returns only public fields.
- Edit profile:
  - Container loads `/api/profile/me`.
  - Submit `PATCH /api/profile` with partial payload.
  - Service validates lengths, reserved words, handle immutability rules.
  - On success, return updated profile; containers update app-level profile cache so header avatar/display name reflect changes.
- Settings:
  - Container fetches `/api/settings`.
  - `PATCH /api/settings` persists notification/privacy toggles.
- Avatar upload lifecycle:
  - Frontend requests `POST /api/profile/avatar/upload-url` with file metadata (name, size, mime).
  - Service validates size/type, generates storage URL or pre-signed upload URL, stores pending reference if needed.
  - Client uploads directly to storage; on success, calls `POST /api/profile/avatar/confirm` with final URL/key.
  - Service updates `avatarUrl`, optionally deletes old avatar.
  - `DELETE /api/profile/avatar` clears `avatarUrl` and triggers deletion.

## 7) Layout & Navigation Architecture
- App shell:
  - Implemented as a shared layout in `src/app/(app)/layout.tsx` (or similar route group), not per-page duplication.
  - Uses design system components (header, nav items, avatar, buttons, icons).
- Desktop:
  - Persistent side nav with primary sections: Home/Feed, Explore (if present), Profile, Settings (and placeholders for later features).
  - Header may show logo/brand and user avatar + quick actions.
- Mobile:
  - Top nav or bottom bar (UI/UX to choose, but constraint is “no desktop side nav”).
  - Collapsible menu or tab-like navigation to same primary sections.
- Containers:
  - Navigation containers decide which item is active based on route.
  - UI components for nav items remain dumb (receive `active`, `icon`, `label`, `href`).

## 8) Frontend Architecture (per CODEBASE_ARCHITECTURE_RULES)
- Containers:
  - `src/components/containers/profile/ProfilePageContainer.tsx`:
    - Fetch current or other profile via services/api client.
    - Pass normalized data to dumb profile UI component(s).
  - `src/components/containers/profile/EditProfileContainer.tsx`:
    - Fetch current profile, manage form state, call profile service.
  - `src/components/containers/settings/SettingsPageContainer.tsx`:
    - Fetch and update settings, manage toggles.
  - `src/components/containers/layout/AppShellContainer.tsx`:
    - Provide layout props (nav items, active state, user summary).
- UI Components (`src/components/ui` and/or `src/components/profile` for composite UI):
  - Purely presentational: profile header, avatar+meta block, stats row, settings form sections, nav list.
  - No data fetching or business logic.
- Networking:
  - All HTTP calls via existing single API client in `src/services/apiClient.ts`.
  - Frontend services `profileApi` / `settingsApi` wrap endpoints; no inline `fetch`.

## 9) Privacy & Visibility Rules
- Public profile:
  - Only serves explicitly public fields: avatar, displayName, handle, bio, location (if `showLocation` true), joinDate, follower/following counts.
- Settings vs profile:
  - Email and legal name (if any) are **never** returned from public profile endpoints.
- Discoverability:
  - `isDiscoverable` controls whether a profile appears in discovery/search (search feature out-of-scope here but flag exists).
- Avatar NSFW:
  - This task **does not** filter or classify avatars.
  - UI copy must state avatars must follow community guidelines and may be moderated later.
  - Future moderation tasks will handle detection, reporting, and enforcement.

## 10) Non-Functional & Performance
- All profile/settings endpoints protected by auth; rate limits on write paths.
- Avatar images:
  - Use existing media pipeline (CDN/resizing handled there).
  - Prefer responsive image components on the frontend (design system aware).
- Caching:
  - Profile responses can be cached client-side; server response should be fast (simple selects/joins).

## 11) Testing Strategy (for Engineering)
- Unit:
  - Services: profile updates (validation, ownership), settings updates, avatar lifecycle logic.
- Integration:
  - Repositories with DB, including unique handle constraints and safe updates.
  - API routes with auth middleware, ensuring privacy rules hold (no email in public profile).
- E2E (later QA task references):
  - View own profile, edit, and verify data reflected in header/nav.
  - View other profile with only public fields.
  - Avatar upload/replace/remove flows.
  - Settings toggles persist and change behavior where applicable.

## 12) Out of Scope (Confirmed)
- Creator-specific profile customization, monetization settings, analytics dashboards.
- Admin views and moderation tooling.
- Fine-grained notification matrix.
- Payment/subscription/payout settings.
- Full IA/secondary nav; only primary sections needed for MVP.

## 13) Approvals Needed
- Human approval of this architecture.
- After approval:
